sections.name: Notice Arrangement of Audiometric Test Form 18

groups.label: Notice is hereby given that I have arranged for you to undergo an audiometric test to be conducted by:
Name of person approved under regulation 19B
Employer WorkCover No (obtainable from your insurer)
A worker shall not, without a reasonable excuse, fail to submit themselves to an audiometric test of which the worker has notice (regulation 19D(3)).

n employer shall ensure that the worker is not knowingly exposed in the workplace, and the worker shall not knowingly permit himself to be exposed, to noise level above 80dB(A) during 16 hours immediately preceding the audiometric test (regulation19D(2)).
To be completed at the start of the appointment
Confirm that I have observed the period of quiet.
I authorise the release of my WorkCover WA Audiometric test results to:
Approved Audiometric Officers to maintain a copy of this form.
Audiologists please return completed form to:
Noise Induced Hearing Loss WorkCover WA 2 Bedbrook Place SHENTON PARK WA 6008
Workers’ Compensation and Injury Management Regulations 1982

(2) WorkCover WA shall, on the written request of the worker tested, communicate the results of an audiometric test delivered to it under clause 4(2) to any person specified by the worker in that request.

(3) A person who receives the results of an audiometric test under subregulation (2) shall ensure that the results of the test, and any information derived from those results are not communicated to any person other than the worker except at the written request of the worker tested
Must be given to the worker within one month of the date of the test being completed.
Here are the results of your hearing test and what they mean.
An audiogram shows the softest level at which a person can hear a range of different pure tones.
The softest sounds that you responded to are marked O for the right ear an X for the left ear. These are your hearing threshold levels.
As a benchmark, normal hearing falls between 0 and 20 dB.

Degrees of hearing loss:              Mild loss
                                                     25-45 dB
                                                     Moderate loss
                                                      50-65 dB
                                                     Severe loss
                                                       70-90 dB
                                                      Profound loss
                                                      95 dB+

All the major sounds of speech are contained within the audiogram range. The approximate volume and pitch of various speech sounds are shown on the audiogram above. This may give you an indication of the sounds you hear less clearly.
You have three months from the date of receiving these results to notify WorkCover WA that you wish to disagree with the results.
To be actioned by Human Resources or Recruitment Advisor and returned to REDIMED within 12 weeks of the test date.
REDIMED completed a work cover compliant hearing test on:

New CheckIn order that our Audiometric Officers may enter this ‘Compliance Hearing Test’ in to the WorkCover WA database within the required time frame, we need to confirm if the applicant stated above is now employed.
If REDIMED receives this form 12 weeks following the hearing test date, in accordance with Work Cover regulations, we will not be permitted to enter these results in to the Work Cover database.
